<p>...resulting in even fewer jobs by increasing motivation for store owners to install kiosks and develop and urge use of smartphone apps for ordering and paying for your order instead of interacting with a front counter worker.</p>
<p>(Actually, I wish they would do this anyway. I'd much rather order my food before I leave wherever I'm coming from or even from the parking lot without waiting in an "order taking" line and THEN waiting for the "food assembly" phase.)</p>
<p>The ratio of jobs that are unskilled or low skill will steadily decline simply because they will continue to be replaced by technology based rather than mindless human labor solutions even if we don't increase the minimum wage. Increasing the minimum wage substantially will just increase the rate of decline resulting in the few lucky people who capture these jobs being happier, but those that now could not get a job being in an even more dire situation.</p>
<p>Also, if we raise the minimum wage substantially (say to $22/hour or about $44K/year as a linked article up-thread hinted at), some people who would previously have increased their skills via education/training to get a better paying job will instead opt for the minimum wage jobs. These new entrants into the pool of minimum wage workers will, I suspect, be the most qualified and best workers (as they were the ones with motivation and intelligence to escape the minimum wage pool when the pay was bad) and will take many of the minimum wage jobs that they previously would not have applied for.</p>
<p>Of course, obviously salaries up the entire range will increase dramatically if one institutes a minimum wage of such absurd proportions as $22/hour. Why would someone bother to spend the time, energy, and money to get training and certifications to work in a stressful IT job for slightly above what they could get in a minimum wage job? These rampant salary increases would, of course, increase inflation which would result in everyone with full time employment about where they were before the minimum wage increase -- but those that had their work hours cut or can't find a job (due to the increased rate of technology adoption replacing now more expensive minimum wage workers) will be in much worse shape.</p>

