<p>the worker...in all industries. &nbsp;The business owner takes the initial risk and puts up the capital to get the business started. &nbsp;The owner often operates in the red for several years until the business is established and forgoes their own personal bills to put it all in the business....sometimes, at the this point, the workers might indeed even make more than the owner himself...it is actually common for this to occur.</p>
<p>Once the business is established, the owner pays all the business taxes, fees, licensing, business insurance, advertisement, building upkeep, maintenance, security, IT costs, equipment cost (copiers, fax machines, water coolers, computers, machines, specialty equipment etc) supplies to run the office (paper, ink, pens, desks, chairs, refrigerators, post it notes, toilet paper, tissues etc)....you get the point. &nbsp;The workers do not have to pay any of this....nor worry about where the money comes from if it is needed and that month runs short. &nbsp;If this occurs, it is up to the owner to secure a loan or sell personal property of whatever.</p>
<p>Once the business is a success, I see no reason that a business owner would not make more than the workers...some who may be only entry level workers and who complete only one small part of the business model. &nbsp;They wouldn't have had a job in the first place, had it not been for the capital, drive and productivity of the business owner in the first place.</p>

